Thinking Constitution Engine — Project Context (Canonical)

Status: Foundational / Kernel-first
Design posture: Models-first, domain-agnostic, audit-first, integration-later

1. Purpose (Why this project exists)

(Unchanged)

The Thinking Constitution Engine (TCE) is a domain-agnostic cognitive kernel designed to govern how decisions and optimizations are made, not what is decided.

It exists to address a specific class of modern failures in decision systems:

Information overload and frame contamination

Implicit value smuggling into optimization pipelines

Overconfident action under epistemic uncertainty

Lack of auditability, review, and learning

Rather than acting as an “ultimate decision maker,” the TCE is a constitutional decision-support framework that:

Preserves human agency

Makes uncertainty first-class and explicit

Requires declared values, objectives, and constraints

Produces proportionate, explainable recommendations

Enables structured learning over time through review

The engine sits above any optimization mechanism
(rules, heuristics, ML, GPT, scoring systems) and governs their use, not replaces them.

2. Core Design Principles (Non-negotiable)

(Unchanged in meaning; enforcement clarified)

These principles are enforced structurally and mechanically, not aspirationally.

Epistemic Sovereignty
No external interpretation has authority without passing through internal process.

Observation Primacy
All reasoning must ground itself in observations, not narratives or conclusions.

Model Provisionality
Models are tools, not truths; assumptions must be explicit and disposable.

Orientation Explicitness
Values, objectives, constraints, and risk posture must be stated, not inferred.

Proportionate Action
Action intensity must scale with confidence, uncertainty, impact, and reversibility.

Auditability
Every output must be traceable to its inputs and assumptions.

Review & Compression
Outcomes feed back into assumptions, weights, and future behavior.

These principles are enforced via:

Immutable models

Constitutional invariants

Runtime validation (non-throwing, auditable)

3. Conceptual Scope (What this is / is not)

(Unchanged)

This project is:

A cognitive kernel

A governance layer for optimization engines

A structured decision pipeline

A reusable foundation across domains

This project is not:

A single optimization algorithm

A black-box AI decision maker

A product, UI, or workflow tool

Tied to any one application (e.g., Assist Network)

Applications consume the engine; they do not define it.

4. High-Level Architecture

(Clarified to reflect invariant execution)

The engine enforces a canonical loop:

Observe → Model → Orient → Act → Review

Each stage produces typed, immutable artifacts that are:

Stored independently

Linked by explicit provenance

Auditable without replaying logic

A DecisionEpisode provides an index-only container over the loop, enabling:

Validation

Audit

Review

Comparison over time

All transitions between stages are constitutionally gated by invariants.

5. Kernel Model Inventory (Foundational)

(Models unchanged; enforcement clarified)

Ingress / Reality

RawInput — Immutable record of what entered the system

Evidence — Provenance anchors (sources, spans, integrity confidence)

Observation — Reality-anchored facts, measurements, testimony

Interpretation / Modeling

Interpretation — Structured hypotheses or explanations

Assumption — Explicit assumptions with confidence and uncertainty

ModelSpec / ModelState — Declared model families and state

Orientation / Values

Orientation — Objectives, constraints, weights, risk posture

Objective — Goals with explicit weighting

Constraint — Hard must-not-violate boundaries

ValueSignal — Normative preferences (non-binding)

Action

Option — Possible actions (pre-recommendation), with:

Impact

Reversibility

Uncertainty

Provenance references

Recommendation — Ranked, explainable, uncertainty-aware proposals

Feedback

Outcome — What actually happened

ReviewRecord — Learning artifacts:

Assumption failures

Calibration errors

Updates and next questions

Governance

InfoType taxonomy — Explicit typing of information

DecisionEpisode — Index-only container

AuditTrail / Lineage — Full trace from action back to reality

6. Information Typing (Critical Design Choice)

(Unchanged)

All information is explicitly typed to prevent contamination:

Observational — events, measurements, testimony

Interpretive — claims, explanations, hypotheses

Normative — values, preferences, constraints

Predictive — forecasts, scenarios

Decision artifacts (Options, Recommendations, Outcomes) are not information and are governed separately.

Constitutional Rule:
No information may influence action without declared type, provenance, and confidence.

